************************************************************************************************************** STRING COMPRESSION ***********************************************************************************************************************************************

Intuition:

We scan the string character by character and observe that only consecutive identical characters matter for compression.

Each time the character changes, it means the current group has ended and its frequency is finalized.

So, we record the character along with how many times it appeared consecutively, preserving the original order.

This process builds a compressed version where every character contributes exactly once per group.

Finally, we compare the lengths of the original and compressed strings and return the shorter one as required.

Approach:

We want to compress the string by grouping consecutive identical characters and storing their frequencies.

A new group starts only when the current character differs from the previous one.

As long as characters are the same, we just increase the count of the current group.

We first process the string:

If the current character matches the last stored character, increment its count.

Otherwise, start a new (character, count) group.

Then we build the compressed string:

Extract each stored group in order and append character + count to the result string.
Finally, if the compressed string is shorter than the original, return it. Otherwise, return the original string as required.
********************************************************************************************************************* PSEDUO CODE ************************************************************************************************
strCompression(s) {
    /* begin program execution */
    create empty structure groups
    /* to store characters and their consecutive counts */

    for (i in range of 0 to length(s) - 1) {
        /* traverse the string from left to right */
        if (groups is not empty AND last character in groups == s[i]) {
            increment count of last character
            /* same character continues, increase frequency */
        } else {
            add (s[i], 1) to groups
            /* new character group starts */
        }
    }

    initialize compressed as empty string
    /* to build the compressed result */

    for (each (char, count) in groups in order) {
        append char followed by count to compressed
        /* form character + frequency */
    }

    if (length(compressed) < length(s)) {
        return compressed
        /* compressed string is shorter */
    }

    return s
    /* return original string otherwise */
}
/* program execution completed */
************************************************************************************************************ C++ CODE **********************************************************************************************************

#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

class solution {
public:
    string strCompression(string s) {
        stack<pair<char, int>> st;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            if (!st.empty() && st.top().first == s[i]) {
                st.top().second++;
            } else {
                st.push({s[i], 1});
            }
        }
        string compressed = "";
        while (!st.empty()) {
            compressed = st.top().first + to_string(st.top().second) + compressed;
            st.pop();
        }
        return compressed.size() < s.size() ? compressed : s;
    }
};

